<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">How Our Pricing Works</p>
    <h2>Labor and parts quoted separately &mdash; here&rsquo;s why that matters</h2>
    <div class="body-text">
      <p>Most appliance repair companies in Los Angeles use flat-rate BlueBook pricing &mdash; a single bundled number that covers labor and parts before the technician has opened the unit. It sounds convenient. But it means you have no idea how much is labor, how much is the specific part, or whether either number is fair for your actual repair.</p>
      <p>We quote differently. The $89 diagnostic fee covers the service call and the full diagnosis. Once we know exactly what failed, we give you two numbers: labor and the specific OEM part needed. You see the full breakdown before we start. You know what you&rsquo;re paying for.</p>
      <p>A flat-rate quote before diagnosis is either padded with margin for uncertainty, or it doesn&rsquo;t change regardless of how simple the job turns out to be. Our model means you pay for what the repair actually requires. A clogged drain with no part needed is not the same job as a compressor replacement &mdash; and your invoice shouldn&rsquo;t treat them as if they were.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="transparency-block">
      <div class="tr-card them">
        <h3>Flat-Rate BlueBook pricing</h3>
        <ul class="tr-list">
          <li>Single price before diagnosis</li>
          <li>Labor and parts bundled &mdash; no breakdown</li>
          <li>You don&rsquo;t know what the part costs</li>
          <li>Price padded to cover uncertainty on every job</li>
          <li>Doesn&rsquo;t adjust based on actual complexity</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="tr-card us">
        <h3>Our approach &mdash; labor + parts separate</h3>
        <ul class="tr-list">
          <li>Diagnose first, then quote</li>
          <li>Labor and parts shown as separate line items</li>
          <li>You see exactly what the OEM part costs</li>
          <li>Price reflects the actual repair needed</li>
          <li>$89 diagnostic applied to the total</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Labor Rates by Repair Type &mdash; Los Angeles 2026</p>
    <h2>What freezer repair labor costs in Los Angeles</h2>
    <p class="lead">All prices are labor only. Parts quoted separately after diagnosis. $89 diagnostic applied to repair total when you approve the work.</p>
    <div class="price-table-wrap">
      <table class="price-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Repair Type</th><th>Labor Range</th><th>What&rsquo;s Typically Involved</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><div class="repair-type">Not freezing / warm freezer</div><div class="repair-desc">Most common call &mdash; freezer not holding temperature, food thawing</div></td>
            <td><div class="price-labor">$200&ndash;$440</div><div class="price-parts-note">+ parts (varies)</div></td>
            <td>Compressor relay, evaporator fan motor, thermostat, condenser coil cleaning</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><div class="repair-type">Frost buildup on back wall</div><div class="repair-desc">Ice building up inside, cooling loss over time</div></td>
            <td><div class="price-labor">$200&ndash;$410</div><div class="price-parts-note">+ parts</div></td>
            <td>Defrost heater, defrost thermostat, defrost timer or control board defrost circuit</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><div class="repair-type">Freezer too cold &mdash; items frozen solid</div><div class="repair-desc">Temperature not cycling correctly, over-freezing</div></td>
            <td><div class="price-labor">$150&ndash;$320</div><div class="price-parts-note">+ parts</div></td>
            <td>Thermostat replacement, temperature sensor, control board calibration or replacement</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><div class="repair-type">Loud noise / vibration</div><div class="repair-desc">Rattling, humming, buzzing from the freezer</div></td>
            <td><div class="price-labor">$150&ndash;$360</div><div class="price-parts-note">+ parts if needed</div></td>
            <td>Evaporator or condenser fan motor, compressor mounts, loose drain pan</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><div class="repair-type">Door gasket replacement</div><div class="repair-desc">Door not sealing, frost near door edges, warm spots</div></td>
            <td><div class="price-labor">$120&ndash;$280</div><div class="price-parts-note">+ OEM gasket</div></td>
            <td>Remove old gasket, install new OEM gasket, verify seal on all edges. LA dry heat dries gaskets faster than humid climates.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><div class="repair-type">Leaking water</div><div class="repair-desc">Water pooling inside freezer or on floor</div></td>
            <td><div class="price-labor">$150&ndash;$340</div><div class="price-parts-note">+ parts if needed</div></td>
            <td>Drain tube clog or damage, defrost drain repair, door seal failure</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><div class="repair-type">Compressor replacement</div><div class="repair-desc">Freezer not cooling at all &mdash; compressor failed</div></td>
            <td><div class="price-labor">$380&ndash;$710</div><div class="price-parts-note">+ compressor (significant cost)</div></td>
            <td>Compressor replacement including refrigerant evacuation, recharge, and leak test. We assess repair vs. replace before proceeding.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><div class="repair-type">Control board failure</div><div class="repair-desc">Erratic temperature, display issues, multiple systems failing</div></td>
            <td><div class="price-labor">$280&ndash;$540</div><div class="price-parts-note">+ board (expensive on some brands)</div></td>
